segments.text: This is an interview with Mrs. Bertha Moore by Larry W. Cruz on April 15, 1976, at the LaSalle Retirement Home at the corner of West 27th at Main in Bryan, Texas.
So tell me a little bit more about Japan.
Well, uh...
I was born, you want me to tell you when I was born?
Yeah, tell it, when you were born.
I was born at about two miles, I used to say I discovered America, about two miles northeast of Bryan in a little neighborhood they called Woodville.
And we moved to Bryan and moved into a, it was kind of like a mining town hotel.
was just across the street west of the First National Bank.
And it was a two-story outfit.
One night, one fellow, somebody was climbing the post to get free lodging, you know.
But we got, my father, mother got out, and they got him.
He come on through, and we seen him back downstairs, you know.
And we had...
Well, the room and board was very cheap, if I remember correctly.
It was $20 a month, you know, for room and board.
We didn't stay there very long.
And one thing about our family, we have lived on Bryan Street ever since we've been in Bryan.
Really?
When we first moved to town, we moved to this hotel.
And then we gave it, when we wanted to get away from the hotel business,
So we moved north on Bryan Street at a little place.
The old man had a cabinet shop in the corner of the yard.
And we children spent most of our time in the cabinet shop.
And he let us use all of his tools and everything.
Then my father bought a house across the street.
Dr. Hall lived there.
And he sold his house and moved into Bryan, further into Bryan.
And we bought that house.
And then when we got rid of that house, we moved to South Bryan, 700 South Bryan.
It's in the house right next door to the woman's old building, the woman's club old building there.
And then when Mr. Moore and I were married, we lived across the street here from the Missouri Pacific Depot.
Yeah, I know where that is.
And now I'm in the hotel, and the back end of the hotel is on Bryan Street.
Oh, golly.
I've lived on Bryan Street ever since I've been in Bryan.
What did your father do?
He was a cotton warehouse man.
He worked in what was known as Bryan Brick Warehouse, and it was down here right where?
Now, what building is there?
part of it faced on Main Street.
I forget what's there now.
But he worked there.
That's one reason we moved to town, because he had to come into town to work, you know.
And then now there's another one.
So he worked there.
That's the main thing he did.
He kind of got into some insurance business, but he didn't stay there.
But his main business was the warehouse.
And they had a wagon yard attached to the warehouse.
And the men who brought the cotton in just camped there that night, you know, and then left the next morning going home.
And we had a warehouse down there.
Then the parker,
Mr. Sam Parker had a warehouse down on North Main Street.
A fellow, an Italian, came in one day.
I was driving for a mule team and loaded with cotton, you know, the wagons loaded with cotton.
And I met the attendant there and said, and what's your name?
And for instance, he said, well, Tony Scaniato or some kind of Italian name.
And came in the next few days, and he had another big wagon load.
This time he had a six-mule team.
And he says, and what's your name?
And he told him again what his name was.
Came in the next week, had a big wagon load of cotton, and he says, and what's your name?
He said, seemed like it was yesterday.
But Father did, he had, he was, we, my folks were the first people
Among the first Presbyterian membership here, they came from a little place out here north of Ryan called Concord.
And my father was superintendent of the Sunday school for 25 years.
And when he retired, they gave him a family Bible, a great big family Bible.
And the Presbyterian church is down here where the city hall is now.
And it faced west.
It was like
The church was just like a big white country church, you know, and had two front doors and an entrance hall, and of course had the steeple and the bell.
But the Galveston storm blew the steeple off and the bell fell.
But they still have the bell.
It's stored in somewhere.
But we've had two churches now, and they haven't put the bell up yet.
There are a lot of Presbyterians around here in the area?
Oh, yeah.
We have a nice congregation.
We have a beautiful church now.
I worked in the church and did everything from sweeping the floors to teaching a Sunday school class.
As I say, I don't know dates.
Oh, that doesn't make any difference.
You said about the Galveston storm blew down the bell?
Oh, yeah.
It blew the steeple.
They never did put the steeple back on.
And what was the question you made?
I've heard about the storm.
Was that the one that just flooded the whole island or something like that?
Well, now, you know, Carla, yes, that was the one that was, yeah.
We had a great big book about this long and about that wide.
And it was, when I had to move up here, everything got lost, you know.
But we had that garrison storm portrayed from one end to the other.
The convents were boomed, were drowned out, you know, and everything.
But Carla did a lot of damage, but that's more recent, you know.
What about something more about your brothers and sisters?
How many brothers and how many sisters did you have?
There was eleven children in the family.
We had five boys and six girls.
I don't want this to go on tape.
We lived family style.
And we all worked together.
We had a big garden spot.
We had three cows.
Now, we were living in town.
There was not very many ordinances then.
We had three cows.
And we had a small peat pen off to one side.
And we had a long grape arbor in the garden with grapes just hung like that.
And we all had a wonderful, wonderful garden.
We lived at home.
Well, we would kill.
We didn't have ice boxes to keep the meats in.
We would salt it down.
It was put down in brine, and some of the meats we took out was just real good breakfast bacon, you know.
My father had a good preservative recipe, you know.
It was salt, peat, and sugar, and I don't know what all, something.
But we lived at home, and we just didn't have much money, but
We had a nice home to live in.
That's the main thing, yeah.
Well, what about, you said you came from a school of hard knocks.
Any way back before that?
Well, I mean that, what I mean is that we didn't have any money for us to have a college education.
Yeah, what about your elementary or education?
Well, I went to our school, had ten grades, and I went through the ninth grade.
But there was a private school here and my sister just younger than I, Mrs. Tina Johnson, who passed away a couple of weeks ago, she and I were living in walking distance of this private school.
It was kind of a college.
And I had a chance to get some botany, some trigonometry, and things like that that I didn't get in the public school.
The superintendent of this little college gave mother a chance to send the two of us at a reduced price, you see.
And we both graduated the same year.
Tinny was salutatorian and I was valedictorian.
We had three, what do you call it, three grades.
There was first prize, well not first prize,
What would it be?
First notation?
And then I was second.
I was second in the graduating class.
And in this school, we had debates.
We had public debates.
And I liked it because we had the botany and we had trigonometry.
And then we had a very good music teacher there, too, you see.
So it was really a nice place to go.
And that, right now,
There's the Newman Printing Company on the grounds.
Oh, really?
Uh-huh.
It was a big two-story house, white house, and it was called the Masonic Hall.
And when that was torn down, this other building was put up there.
I was glad that I got this education.
We only had reading, writing, and arithmetic in high school.
You said you had a good music teacher?
Did you play any instruments or anything?
Well, we had an elderly lady from north, up north somewhere, but she was a good instructress.
But we had some, what do you call the...
When somebody has a graduation, they have a special program.
Oh, yeah.
Commencement?
No, not a commencement.
A recital.
A recital, yeah.
Thank you for a word.
We had recitals that were very nice.
We had a public place where we had most all of our programs.
It was located down here where this...
First National Bank drive-in bank is, and it was called the Bryan Opera House.
It eventually burned, but we used to have our debates.
You see now you have it at the schools and things, but we didn't have anything like that when I was coming on.
What did you usually debate about?
Just topics of the day?
Well, the biggest thing that, now let's see, was with regard to the Russian, Japanese, and Russian issues.
I mean...
They had a big war or something?
Yeah, oh yeah.
That's when the Russian and Japanese were fighting so badly.
What was the real question?
It was...
There's a word in there that I can't get.
Should America join in or something like that?
No.
Whether it was a good idea for them to
be at, across ways, you know.
But anyhow, my side lost.
There was two boys and two girls.
But oh, I tell you, I did more reading.
I could have fought two or three battles if I'd have had a chance.
And then that school finally folded up.
The man died, the president died, and it folded up.
Anybody home?
No, we're gone.
In your social life, you know, when you were growing up in school or anything, did you have dances or whatever?
Well, I never did dance, I never did throw dice, and I never did drink.
But still, you had a good time.
But I had a real good time, and I knew what I had.
Yeah.
And I had always had a very pleasant situation.
We had lots of things that we attended.
I don't know whether people know anything about it today.
Is that we had hay rides, and we had play parties, and we had a heel and toe dance a lot of times.
And everybody seemed to be in a congenial attitude, you know.
So we didn't have any, none of the things that they have today.
And so far as graduating at the College of Hard Knocks, I had to get mine the best way I could.
And I have gotten most of my education from observation.
I've kept one eye open on all corners.
And we had...
where we'd have recitals, and we called them musicals more than anything.
And all I did was to go and listen because I didn't, in fact I couldn't carry a tune in a sack, I don't think.
But we had always, and we had lots of parties
maybe a public place chaperoned by some fewer ladies.
But we always had a very nice, mostly the weekends, you know.
The rest of the time was devoted to the books.
And I never did absorb much of them.
But now, my work has been volunteer work.
I worked at different places in town.
I worked at the telephone office, I worked at the drug store, and I worked at...
Were you a telephone operator?
I was a telephone operator for several years.
Really good many years.
I worked in the time when we cranked the bells, cranked the switchboard.
The manager of the telephone company said, Well, since you've done everything in the telephone company now, but climb a pole.
But he would go out on the line, you know, and have a test phone with him and call in and pick up the trouble, and I would be able to locate it on the switch on the...
The board back of the switchboard, you know.
But I worked at all places in the telephone office, long distance and rural and local.
One lady called me one day and said, I'm going to cross the street.
I'm going to put the baby by the phone.
and take the receiver down, and if he cries, will you call me?
So I babysit it, too.
Over the telephone?
Over the telephone.
Golly.
So that's the way we lived in that day and time.
You know, there's a lot of contact.
I don't think anybody would do that now.
But in my later years, I have over 35 years with the Red Cross.
what used to be the Grey Ladies.
We don't have the Grey Ladies anymore.
And counting the, and we worked, one lady and I, Mrs. Lyons and I, went to Marlin and made arrangements to work at the Marlin Veterans Hospital.
And I have had, I was one of the, well I was the first one that got the 1,000 hour
The pen for 1,000 hours of volunteer work.
We have several who have gotten those hours, too.
We've had a good group that has worked at Marlin every week.
Four or five go up and do what they call pilot service.
And they were the Red Cross gray ladies then, but now they are the Brazos volunteer.
Brazos area volunteer group.
This week.
And she's one of them.
She went up to Marlin this week.
And we work for the day up there.
We leave about 7 o'clock in the morning and get back about 4.
We got back about 10 minutes to 4.
Did you?
We generally made it in a long time ago.
We made it in about 5, but then between 4 and 5, you know.
And so, and I have, since I've not been able to participate physically, I've done volunteer work.
here.
For instance, these things I'm making.
I work with the church.
My group at the church works with the indigent people, you know, to a certain extent.
And we make something out of nothing.
We take a man's shirt and we cut the collar off and use the front part for a baby gown.
We put laced
down the front part and at the collar.
We take a part of the tail of the shirt and make the sleeves and put lace on that.
And we have that for the gown, or for the little gown you might say.
And we take the tail of the shirt and make a diaper shirt out of it.
And we'll take the, if it's a long sleeve shirt, there's a bi-side and a straight side to the sleeve.
We'll sew that together.
and then we peek over the outside edge of it and make a diaper.
Then when we get ready to dispose of them, we make what they call a lead.
We put in two or three of these gowns and the little butterfly baby jackets and two or three dresses and three or four dozen diapers.
Then we put that all in a package and take it to the courthouse to this office where they dispose of them.
The people who get them, I think, are screened.
And they give them to some of them that don't have things to start off with.
So that's one thing I do.
This goes into that, too, you see.
And I have made, this is called a wheelchair lap robe.
Mm-hmm.
I made 50 of those for the Marlin Hospital in the time that I've been with them.
And then I've made 25 for friends.
Some of them have a father in a nursing home.
And then I made my niece one and two or three people in California.
I've made some for a lady who lives.
She used to visit us.
Her son was in the Navy and she used to visit us.
I made two for her.
And things like that, you know.
But I put my hours in the volunteer group because I still have my name on the calendar, I mean on the list.
I make myself belong.
I don't know whether I need to believe that, but I just didn't want to give it up.
So I stay with them.
I do do that.
And in that work, I have
I've rejuvenated bedspreads, a lot of knitting work, and our church knitted bandages for the leprosarium over in Africa.
And I've knitted 75 bandages.
When we first started working with them, Larry, we made them 50 inches long.
They're 35 stitches on, 30 stitches on the needle.
And we made them 50 inches long.
And then they went up to 72, then they went to 92, and now we have to do them 96 inches long.
And you know that's a long way.
But we've had pictures from over there where they use these bandages, and they can't use the AC bandages because the rubbers deteriorate so badly, you know.
So they use these bandages, and they can use them over and over.
They take them off and wash them, disinfect them, and use them again, you know.
But they couldn't do the AC bandage.
I've seen several dead AC bandages over there, but I never have heard whether they used them or not.
They might use them for something else.
But this leprosarium, our church has been working, and I think other churches in town,
Worked with the lepersoreum over there, too.
But we do do that.
You know, you were talking about all your jobs and everything.
What about the transportation, you know, to and from?
Did you have an old car or a wagon or a bugger or something?
Well, when we had our original, we walked.
Yeah, that's the thing.
What'd you say, Willa Beth?
We walked.
Yeah, we walked.
Then maybe somebody, but I never did get a ride to work, you know, the work that I did.
But now they have, in the group going to Marlin, one lady takes her car and they, isn't it the group that goes together and pays for the gas?
We pay for our gas.
We pay for the gas.
Now when we were gray ladies...
The Red Cross furnished the gas for us.
They don't do it anymore though now.
We had a divorce.
We'll have to have a barbecue or something.
Each member pays a dollar a month, but if we don't have too many members... We don't have near the...
It gets pretty high.
We don't have near the members that we used to have.
What about...
about your marriage with Mr. Moore.
Can you tell me more about what was he like?
Mr. Moore was, when I met him, he was, they called them drummers in that day and time.
He was a salesman for an implement company out of Dallas.
And I worked with Parker Ashton Hardware Company.
And we had
It looked like, well, it was several years before we were married.
But we were married at home.
And we went to Mejia for a few days and came back.
And he was, at the time that I married him, he was agent for the Seth Moring Plantation in the Brazos Abaddon, in the Mudville area.
They had the house fixed up before we were married, and we moved down there and lived in, oh, we stayed down there quite a few years.
I forget, maybe six, eight years.
And then he took over the Magnolia Agency in Bryan, and we moved back to Bryan.
And that's when we moved over here across from the depot.
And he, we were married in 1915, and he died in,
I've been a widow three times as long as I was married.
I've had a hard fight with a short stick.
But I had one son who, if I do say it myself, he really made his name in the military, in the Air Force.
If you could see some of the
honors that were some of the awards and things that he received.
When did he go into the Air Force?
Beg your pardon?
When did he go into the Air Force?
In, um, wait a minute.
What had I done?
41, I believe.
He tried to, look over there and get that black book.
This book here?
Yeah.
That was a command, not an entreaty.
He tried to get in up here.
This has all been stored away.
I had to go to the hospital and they had to give up my room here.
All this has been stored away.
So it's in pretty bad shape.
This is where he was in school and he was king of
And this is very... Now when he tried to get in here in Bryan, they found he was colorblind.
And he couldn't get in.
He went back to college and tried.
They had the recruiting office that was under the grandstand down there.
He didn't get in.
But when they heard this
They were in Houston.
He went to Houston, but he got behind a boy who was just going in.
And he saw, he remembered what it was, you know.
But he never did, he would never, he never got into officer's training, anything like that, because he wouldn't go in.
He said if they would throw a green light or a red light, he wouldn't know which is which.
But he made master sergeant.
And he was a turret gunner.
And he got an award in Italy and in England.
And when he was in the islands, he gave blood for one of the main Rotarians down there.
And he was given quite a bit of publicity then.
And there's been so many awards.
that you just can't realize that he's done as many as he did.
And he was living in Tucson, Arizona when he was killed.
He was in Davis Month in the Air Force Base out there.
And... Sound like a real fine person?
Well, you know, everybody thinks our crew is the blackest.
Yeah.
I know what you mean.
Yeah.
But he was...
He really was a wonderful...
